Question 1

(a) Identify the type of Operating System suitable for this environment and justify your answer.

A Multi-User Operating System (Linux) is the most suitable operating system for a university computer laboratory where multiple students execute programs simultaneously on a shared server. A multi-user operating system allows many users to access the same computer system at the same time without affecting each other's work. Each user has a separate login account, memory space, files, and permissions. The operating system efficiently manages CPU scheduling, memory allocation, process execution, and file access among all users. Linux also provides security, multitasking, process isolation, and resource sharing, making it reliable and efficient for educational institutions and enterprise environments.

(b) State any two responsibilities of the kernel in managing multiple user processes.

1. Process Management
The kernel is responsible for creating, scheduling, synchronizing, and terminating processes. It allocates CPU time to each process using scheduling algorithms so that multiple users can run their programs efficiently without conflicts.

2. Memory Management
The kernel allocates and deallocates memory to processes whenever required. It also protects the memory of one process from being accessed by another process, ensuring system security and stability.

