Question 4

(a) State the purpose of the fork() and exec() system calls.

fork()
The fork() system call creates a new child process by duplicating the parent process. After execution, both parent and child continue independently. It returns 0 in the child process and the child process ID in the parent process.

exec()
The exec() system call replaces the currently running process with a new program. It loads the new program into memory and begins executing it without creating another process.

(b) Explain the role of the wait() system call.

The wait() system call suspends the execution of the parent process until the child process completes its execution. It ensures proper synchronization between parent and child processes, prevents zombie processes, and allows the parent to obtain the child's exit status.

(c) Write a system call sequence using fork(), exec(), and wait().

#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>

int main() {

    if(fork() == 0)
        execl("/bin/ls", "ls", NULL);
    else
        wait(NULL);

    return 0;
}

Question 5

(a) Explain the importance of file management in an operating system.

File management is one of the most important functions of an operating system. It organizes files and directories, provides efficient storage and retrieval of data, controls file permissions, manages free disk space, and ensures data security. It also supports file creation, deletion, copying, renaming, and backup operations. Proper file management improves system performance and prevents unauthorized access to user data.

(b) State the purpose of the open() and close() system calls.

open()
The open() system call opens an existing file or creates a new file and returns a file descriptor that is used for reading or writing operations.

close()
The close() system call closes the opened file after all operations are completed. It releases the file descriptor, saves any pending changes, and frees the system resources associated with the file.

